00:45:50.040 --> 00:45:57.040
I see another anonymous question that was Excel may be considered as interactive app for data analysis.

00:45:57.040 --> 00:46:05.040
How do you help Excel users successfully transition to a shiny app developer?

00:46:05.040 --> 00:46:06.040
Well, yeah, you're in luck.

00:46:06.040 --> 00:46:11.040
I mean, there are a lot of resources around learning to do shiny.

00:46:11.040 --> 00:46:18.040
So if you go to, what is it, shiny.arcstudio.com, that's a great place to get started.

00:46:18.040 --> 00:46:21.040
The creator of shiny is Joe Chang.

00:46:21.040 --> 00:46:23.040
And shiny is 10 years old now.

00:46:23.040 --> 00:46:24.040
It's been around for a while.

00:46:24.040 --> 00:46:29.040
But the cool thing about shiny is that it was designed to fail nicely.

00:46:29.040 --> 00:46:32.040
So Joe talks about the pit of success, right.

00:46:32.040 --> 00:46:38.040
So you might make a mistake, but shiny is going to be nice to you, you know, when you make that mistake.

00:46:39.040 --> 00:46:43.040
It will find something else to do or it will give you a warning or, you know,

00:46:43.040 --> 00:46:46.040
it will help you try to figure out the best way to do it.

00:46:46.040 --> 00:46:52.040
So the way if you're transitioning to shiny, be nice to yourself, start simple,

00:46:52.040 --> 00:46:56.040
and then just follow the patterns and fall into that pit of success.

00:46:56.040 --> 00:47:02.040
I say that myself because I'm not the world's best shiny app developer.

00:47:02.040 --> 00:47:07.040
My background is in big data, right, as opposed to front-end application design.

00:47:07.040 --> 00:47:13.040
But I have learned that just going with the patterns, going with the flow,

00:47:13.040 --> 00:47:16.040
you're going to have a pretty gentle ride with shiny.

00:47:16.040 --> 00:47:20.040
And if you do have problems, go to community.arcstudio.com.

00:47:20.040 --> 00:47:24.040
There's a lot of resources on the community site about doing shiny.

00:47:24.040 --> 00:47:29.040
And you can ask questions like you would in a stack overflow type of situation.

00:47:31.040 --> 00:47:36.040
I think it can also be helpful to check out the shiny gallery too, and I'll put that in the chat.

00:47:36.040 --> 00:47:37.040
Definitely.

00:47:37.040 --> 00:47:43.040
But it can give you a good starting point if you see something that's kind of like what you want to do

00:47:43.040 --> 00:47:45.040
and go from there.

00:47:45.040 --> 00:47:49.040
I will point out one thing that's interesting about shiny is that reactive nature

00:47:49.040 --> 00:47:53.040
is very similar to the Excel paradigm, right?

00:47:53.040 --> 00:47:57.040
So in Excel, you change one cell and it just trickles through the whole spreadsheet

00:47:57.040 --> 00:48:00.040
and can just have massive changes to the experience.

00:48:00.040 --> 00:48:01.040
Shiny is the same way.

00:48:01.040 --> 00:48:08.040
You'll change one thing and it will just reactively, like, percolate through the entire application.

00:48:08.040 --> 00:48:09.040
It's cool.

00:48:09.040 --> 00:48:12.040
It's cool stuff.

