00:53:42.040 --> 00:53:49.040
I wrote a post many years ago when I first joined RStudio about making R legitimate in your organization,

00:53:49.040 --> 00:53:55.040
and the tenets of that was to make a decision and allocate resources.

00:53:55.040 --> 00:54:00.040
So you're looking for a stakeholder, usually someone very senior in your organization,

00:54:00.040 --> 00:54:05.040
to say, we will consider R to be an analytic standard, and we're going to support it,

00:54:05.040 --> 00:54:09.040
just like we would SQL or these other tools that we're talking about.

00:54:09.040 --> 00:54:13.040
And then if you can get resources allocated to them, whether it be, like, you know,

00:54:13.040 --> 00:54:19.040
like a server, like money resources or software, or you get individuals, like saying,

00:54:19.040 --> 00:54:23.040
we're going to train these individuals on those things, that's what you're looking for, right?

00:54:23.040 --> 00:54:27.040
And that's the natural process in most organizations to recognize standards.

00:54:27.040 --> 00:54:33.040
And they're just – because R is fairly small, it just hasn't gone through that process.

00:54:33.040 --> 00:54:42.040
There's an assumption that R is – that data science is things that people do on their laptops with free software, right?

00:54:42.040 --> 00:54:46.040
And I think that greatly undermines the value of data science.

00:54:46.040 --> 00:54:51.040
I think that – and it's, you know, Josh pointed out, well, what about Tableau, right?

00:54:51.040 --> 00:54:54.040
And what about Power BI? Power BI is a little different than Microsoft, right?

00:54:54.040 --> 00:54:57.040
