01:13:38.040 --> 01:13:43.040
You'll have to make sure you have permissions to connect to that database.

01:13:43.040 --> 01:13:48.040
But what you normally do is you run the Shiny application either as yourself

01:13:48.040 --> 01:13:53.040
or as a service account that has permissions to access that database.

01:13:53.040 --> 01:13:57.040
And then the tools are you're just going to use the same R tools

01:13:57.040 --> 01:14:00.040
to pull that data in depending on the user inputs.

01:14:00.040 --> 01:14:02.040
So, for example, say I'm a user

01:14:02.040 --> 01:14:06.040
and I want to like access my Oracle database

01:14:06.040 --> 01:14:10.040
and I want to pull in like the latest sales data, you know.

01:14:10.040 --> 01:14:13.040
You'll go in there and like put a date range,

01:14:13.040 --> 01:14:16.040
and that date range will pass through SQL and the driver

01:14:16.040 --> 01:14:19.040
and pull that data back and populate the Shiny application.

01:14:19.040 --> 01:14:21.040
Very, very common request.

01:14:21.040 --> 01:14:25.040
Very common use case for Shiny.

